Analyze multi-purpose genes in oncolist clusters¶

Author: Brin Rosenthal (sbrosenthal@ucsd.edu)

Table of Contents¶

  1. Notebook summary
  2. Import packages
  3. Load the data
  4. Group the data
  5. Create bipartite graph
  6. Draw the graph

Summary¶

The OSLOM algorithm assigns some genes to multiple clusters, within the same disease, indicating that these genes play a role in multiple functions. In this notebook We take a look at these 'multi-purpose' genes.

A bi-partite network is built using clusters as one node type, and multi-purpose genes as the other node type. Connections are drawn between each multi-purpose gene and the clusters it belongs to WITHIN the same disease. We then combine networks from multiple diseases by summing the edge weights. Note: We don't include single-purpose genes in the graph because by definition, single-purpose genes have degree 1, and thus will never connect to other parts of the graph.

Which genes appear in multiple clusters?¶

  • Load pre-computed DataFrame, containing the following columns:
    • GOname: highest annotating GO term for clusters in which multi-purpose genes are found
    • disease: Disease each multi-purpose gene is found in
    • gene: multi-purpose gene name
    • qval: GO annotation confidence for cluster

DataFrame is computed in 'construct_bilabels_from_clusters.ipynb'

Create bipartite graph from groupby object¶

  • Bipartite graph is created from the data, where nodes are multi-purpose genes, and GOterms, and are weighted by how many diseases the link appears in.
In [11]:
# create a bipartite graph from the data (nodes are genes and GOterms, weighted by how many diseases they appear in)
gene_names = list(np.unique(genes_df['gene']))
disease_dict = {}
edge_list_weighted = []
for g in gene_names:
    genes_GB_g = genes_GB['qval'][g]
    [GOtemp,Dtemp] = zip(*dict(genes_GB_g).keys())
    GO_D_dict = dict(zip(GOtemp,Dtemp))
    
    if g in disease_dict.keys():
        disease_dict[g].extend(list(Dtemp))
    else:
        disease_dict[g] = list(Dtemp)
    
    GOtemp_unique = list(np.unique(GOtemp))
    for GO in GOtemp_unique:
        edge_list_weighted.append((g,GO,len(genes_GB_g[GO])))
        
        if GO in disease_dict.keys():
            disease_dict[GO].append(GO_D_dict[GO])
        else:
            disease_dict[GO] = [GO_D_dict[GO]]
            
# only keep the unique ones
disease_series = pd.Series(disease_dict)
for key in list(disease_series.index):
    d_unique = list(np.unique(disease_series[key]))
    node_title_temp = key+ ' -- diseases found in: <br/>'
    for d in d_unique:
        node_title_temp += d+'<br/>'
    disease_series[key] = node_title_temp
        
disease_dict = dict(disease_series)
In [12]:
G_MP = nx.Graph()
G_MP.add_weighted_edges_from(edge_list_weighted)

Prep graph for visJS_2_jupyter visualization¶

In [13]:
# prep graph for visJS_2_jupyter visualization
# add BC and CC as attributes
# create nodes_dict and edges_dict for input to visjs
pos = nx.spring_layout(G_MP)

nodes = G_MP.nodes()

numnodes = len(nodes)
edges = G_MP.edges()
numedges = len(edges)

# add a node attributes to color-code by
cc = nx.clustering(G_MP)
degree = G_MP.degree()
bc = nx.betweenness_centrality(G_MP)
nx.set_node_attributes(G_MP,'clustering_coefficient',cc)
nx.set_node_attributes(G_MP,'degree',degree)
nx.set_node_attributes(G_MP,'betweenness_centrality',bc)

# set node_size to degree
node_size = [int(float(n)/np.max(degree.values())*25+1) for n in degree.values()]
node_to_nodeSize = dict(zip(degree.keys(),node_size))

# add nodes to highlight (none for now)
nodes_HL = pd.Series(0,index=G_MP.nodes())
nodes_HL = dict(nodes_HL)

nodes_shape = ['dot' if node in gene_names else 'triangle' for node in G_MP.nodes()]
node_to_nodeShape=dict(zip(G_MP.nodes(),nodes_shape))

# add a field for node labels
node_blank_labels = ['']*len(G_MP.nodes())

node_labels = dict(zip(G_MP.nodes(),node_blank_labels))

# set plotting parameters here

field_to_map='degree'

graph_title = 'Multi-purpose genes'
if field_to_map=='clustering_coefficient':
    graph_title = graph_title = graph_title +'<br/> Nodes color-coded by clustering coefficient'
    color_map=mpl.cm.cool

elif field_to_map=='betweenness_centrality':
    graph_title = graph_title = graph_title +'<br/> Nodes color-coded by betweenness centrality'
    color_map=mpl.cm.spring_r
elif field_to_map=='degree':
    graph_title = graph_title = graph_title +'<br/> Nodes color-coded by degree'
    color_map=mpl.cm.RdPu

                                                  color_max_frac = color_max_frac,color_min_frac = color_min_frac)  # make a new transparent version

nodes_dict = [{"id":n,"degree":G_MP.degree(n),"color":node_to_color[n],

Network | Basic usage
  • Note that the structure in the graph mirrors the GO tree structure, but this is non-trivial, because we only impose the GO labels AFTER clustering.

  • This tells us that the OSLOM algorithm is accurately capturing genes which have multiple functions

  • May be useful for researchers looking to explore the data on a gene level
